Here is the detailed solution:

1. Write the reaction and define the extent of reaction \(x\):
   \[
     \ce{CO + H2O <=> CO2 + H2}, 
     \quad
     x > 0\ (\text{forward})
   \]

2. Tabulate initial and equilibrium amounts:
   \[
   \begin{array}{c|cccc}
     & \ce{CO} & \ce{H2O} & \ce{CO2} & \ce{H2} \\\hline
   \text{initial (mol)} 
     & 40 & 40 & 20 & 20 \\
   \text{change (mol)} 
     & -x & -x & +x & +x \\
   \text{equil. (mol)} 
     & 40 - x & 40 - x & 20 + x & 20 + x 
   \end{array}
   \]

3. Since \(\Delta n_{\rm gas}=0\), the total pressure cancels in \(K_p\):
   \[
     K_p \;=\;\frac{p_{\ce{CO2}}\,p_{\ce{H2}}}{p_{\ce{CO}}\,p_{\ce{H2O}}}
     \;=\;
     \frac{\bigl(\tfrac{20+x}{120}\bigr)\,\bigl(\tfrac{20+x}{120}\bigr)}
          {\bigl(\tfrac{40-x}{120}\bigr)\,\bigl(\tfrac{40-x}{120}\bigr)}
     \;=\;
     \frac{(20+x)^2}{(40-x)^2}
     \;=\;0.64.
   \]

4. Solve for \(x\):
   \[
     \frac{20+x}{40-x} = \sqrt{0.64} = 0.8
     \;\Longrightarrow\;
     20 + x = 0.8\,(40 - x)
     \;\Longrightarrow\;
     20 + x = 32 - 0.8x
     \;\Longrightarrow\;
     1.8\,x = 12
     \;\Longrightarrow\;
     x = \frac{12}{1.8} = 6.6667\ \text{mol}.
   \]

5. Thus the equilibrium amount of \(\ce{CO2}\) is
   \[
     n_{\rm CO_2} = 20 + x = 20 + 6.6667 = 26.6667\ \text{mol}
     \approx 26.67\ \text{mol}.
   \]

Final Answer:
\[
\boxed{26.67}\,\mathrm{mol}
\]

